name: Gorilla beringei beringei
occurrenceRemarks: Scientific & Common Name(s) The scientific name for the Mountain Gorilla is Gorilla beringei beringei (Huijbregts, 2018). It is a subspecies of the Eastern Gorilla, and commonly named Gorilla by itself for simplicity. Mature male Mountain Gorillas are also commonly called silverback gorillas. Habitat & Geographic Range Mountain Gorillas live at high altitudes (8000 to 13000) on the slopes of volcanoes in Rwanda, western Uganda and Congo. The gorillas primarily live in the Virunga Mountain chain, stretching through these 3 nations. Due to their limited population, their geographic range is generally limited to these countries, and outside of extremely small populations, to the Virunga Mountains. During his research in the late 1950s George Schaller identified the zones where the gorillas settle, and these zones seemed to depend on the presence and availability of food sources (Schaller, 1966). The type of forests they habituated extend from rainforests to bamboo forests, dense forests and many live in open areas on volcanic slopes. A single Mountain Gorilla will generally have a home zone ranging about 39km. Size/ Weight & Lifespan Male mountain gorillas grow to a mean standing height of 1.5-1.8m with a wing span of 2.25m. They generally weigh up to 204-227kg, while females weigh up to 113-136kg. Given their habitat at high altitudes, the Mountain Gorillas have long, thick silky black (grey in part for the adult males) coats. They also tend to have a stockier physique and shorter arms than gorillas that live in lower altitudes. Their average lifespan when in the wild is 35 years old, however the presence of poachers (normally targeting other animals but inadvertently harming gorillas), hunters, disease resulting from contact with human and ongoing civil wars in their habitats majorly threatens their survival. Diet Mountain Gorillas are primarily herbivorous, mainly foraging for vegetation such as roots, leaves, vines, bark and bamboo of numerous plant species. They also occasionally feed on fruits and small insects, depending on what is readily available. They are said to spend around 30% of the day foraging, which makes sense given their large body masses. Reproduction & Communication Female Mountain gorillas reach sexual maturity much faster than males at around 6 years old versus males who mature around 15 to 20 years old. Mature male gorillas regularly leave the group they are a part of and travel alone in order to establish a group of their own, where they are the dominant male. The reason for this is to gain ready access to mature females, and they remain the dominant alpha male unless another male silverback challenges and ousts it. If another male challenges the alpha, physical prowess is the quality desired, and the gorillas will show their power by aggressively charging, chest pounding and occasionally physical battles. Despite this, they are generally peaceful creatures if not confronted by a predator or competitor. The alpha male organizes group activities such as eating, nesting and foraging (Huijbregts, 2018). Mountain gorilla females tend to give berth every 4 years, and have a gestation period similar to humans at around 9 months. Predation Much like many other species primarily habituating in forests, the Mountain Gorilla’s primary predators are humans. Although not generally targeted by poachers, Moutain Gorillas often get caught in nets and snares set to catch other animals, and can be harmed or killed in these scenarios. Ongoing civil wars in Central Africa have also affected the Gorillas livelihood and habitats, and contact with humans presents a serious risk for the gorillas as they can die from simple human diseases that they have never been in contact with before (Nyakatura, 2009). The only other animal within the Mountain Gorillas range that has the ability to kill an adult is the leopard, as it is extremely fast and can climb trees proficiently. They rarely prey on gorillas, but in the cases that they do they usually avoid the silverbacks and attack the infants of the group. Conservation Status The Mountain Gorilla’s conservation Status is critically endangered, however there has been positive news recently as the population was reported to be above 1000, making it the only great ape population to be increasing at the moment. The risks surrounding the Moutain Gorillas habitat do not bode well for its future, however, but the increasing numbers do provide hope. Did you know? Did you know that Mountain Gorillas have unique nose prints, similar to human’s distinct fingerprints? References Fossey, D., & Harcourt, A. (1977). informationWithheld: Coordinate uncertainty increased to 31448m at the request of the observer
name: Gorilla beringei beringei
occurrenceRemarks: Mwirima the silverback and leader of the Rushegura group in 2012. Adult males are called silverbacks because a saddle of gray or silver-colored hair develops on their backs with age. The hair on their backs is shorter than on most other body parts, and their arm hair is especially long. Fully erect, males reach 1.9 m (6 ft 3 in) in height, with an arm span of 2.3 m (7 ft 7 in) and weigh 220 kg (490 lb). Adult males have more pronounced bony crests on the top and back of their skulls, giving their heads a more conical shape. These crests anchor the powerful temporalis muscles, which attach to the lower jaw (mandible). Adult females also have these crests, but they are less pronounced. Like all gorillas they feature dark brown eyes framed by a black ring around the iris. The fur of the mountain gorilla, often thicker and longer than that of other gorilla species, enables them to live in colder temperatures. Gorillas can be identified by nose prints unique to each individual. Males, at a mean weight of 195 kg (430 lb) and upright standing height of 150 cm (59 in) usually weigh twice as much as the females, at a mean of 100 kg (220 lb) and a height of 130 cm (51 in). More photos of the group » https://tinyurl.com/ewa-bwindi-2012

informationWithheld: Coordinate uncertainty increased to 31448m at the request of the observer
name: Gorilla beringei beringei
occurrenceRemarks: Young gorillas play often and are more arboreal than the large adults. Playing helps them learn how to communicate and behave within the group. Activities include wrestling, chasing and somersault, and just playing around. The silverback and his females tolerate and even participate if encouraged. More photos of the group » https://tinyurl.com/ewa-bwindi-2012

name: Gorilla beringei beringei
occurrenceRemarks: The 2006 census at Bwindi indicated a population of 340 gorillas, representing a 6% increase in total population size since 2002 and a 12% increase from 320 individuals in 1997. All of those estimates were based on traditional census methods using dung samples collected at night nests. Conversely, genetic analyses of the entire population during the 2006 census indicated there were only approximately 300 individuals in Bwindi. The discrepancy highlights the difficulty in using imprecise census data to estimate population growth. More photos of the group » https://tinyurl.com/ewa-bwindi-2012

informationWithheld: Coordinate uncertainty increased to 31448m at the request of the observer
name: Gorilla beringei beringei
occurrenceRemarks: This is Kabukojo. At the time he was a blackback around 12 years of age. Sentinel for the Rushegura group led by Mwirima who died in 2014 (if I am correct). Kabukojo took over Mwirima in a takeover and has been leading the group since then (again if I am still correct as anything can happen quickly in those forests). I am hoping that he and his group are doing well). More photos of the group » https://tinyurl.com/ewa-bwindi-2012
